<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-30T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-30T22:00:00-05:00" n="586" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12606: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-31T11:00:00+08:00">December 31, 1933—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>942. Legation’s 928, December 23, 4 p.m. The following telegram has been
                            received from Amoy: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“December 30, 4 p.m. Referring to my telegram of December 22, 5
                                    p.m. As precautionary measure all Americans at Changchow and <pb facs="0659" n="557" xml:id="pg_557"/> Siokhe have come to
                                    Amoy. All communications unreliable and troops being sent
                                    northward. General Gaston Wang has returned to Amoy. Local
                                    situation remains quiet but tense.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>